<DOC><DOCNO> AP880426-0092 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0906EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Amerasians-MIA     04-26 0310</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Amerasians-MIA,0322</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. Officials Begin Talks On Amerasians, Prepare For MIA SearchIn Laos</HEAD><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. and Vietnamese officials begantalks today on ways to speed up America's resettlement ofVietnamese, including children fathered by American servicemenduring the Vietnam War.   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, saidthe American team at the talks was headed by Bruce Beardsley,director of the embassy's Refugee and Migration Affairs unit.   The Vietnamese delegation is headed by Hoang Quoc Tin, deputydirector of the Foreign Ministry's consular department, said aVietnamese embassy official.   The talks, the latest of the regularly scheduled sessions ontechnical issues, are scheduled to last two days.   U.S. military experts, meanwhile, are completing a survey of awarplane crash site in southern Laos and will soon excavate it tosearch for remains of missing Americans, a U.S. official said today.   The excavation in Savannakhet province will be the third suchU.S.-Laotian effort to account for Americans listed as missing inaction in Laos during the Vietnam War. Savannakhet is in thesouthern panhandle area between Thailand and Vietnam.   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said theAmerican team was being led by Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, commander ofthe U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center headquartered in Honolulu.   More than 500 Americans still are listed as missing in Laos fromthe war in Indochina.   In the negotiations with Vietnam, the two sides are to discussthe processing of Vietnamese under the Orderly Departure Program.   More than 64,000 Vietnamese have been resettled in America underthe program, established in 1980 as an alternative to the tragicboat exodus.   U.S. officials will also discuss America's proposal to resettlewithin two years up to 12,000 Amerasians, or half-Americanchildren, and their immediate families.   The United States thus far has resettled more than 4,000Amerasians.</TEXT></DOC>